{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b29510bf-13d4-4d49-a366-1079ca6808f5","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_019pKkzrvUmDao15AXnH62tU","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Running tests with crash dumps"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01VtFhYSFZnyaFoe8DQj53Pf","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-740126d40de147d98c51b9e19d37c5b4 && dotnet test --blame-crash 2>&1","description":"Run dotnet test with --blame-crash","initial_wait":60},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Run dotnet test with --blame-crash"}],"interactionId":"34042540-89c0-45da-980b-cd7c99e5c1ae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to run `dotnet test` and collect a crash dump if any test crashes the host process. \n\nFor .NET, the standard way to collect crash dumps on process crashes is to use the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` environment variable (or `COMPlus_DbgEnableMiniDump` for older runtimes). \n\nThe relevant environment variables are:\n- `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` — enables mini dump collection on crash\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType` — sets the dump type (1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\n\n\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` — sets the dump file path/name\n\nActually, the more straightforward approach is to use the `--blame-crash` flag with `dotnet test`, which is purpose-built for capturing crash dumps when the test host unexpectedly terminates. I can also specify the dump type with `--blame-crash-dump-type` and use `--blame-crash-collect-always` if needed.\n\nLet me run the tests with `--blame-crash`.","outputTokens":502,"requestId":"0C07:29D6CF:671811:781C52:69F00ECC"},"id":"763d5565-7ce7-408f-8ddc-3be045560152","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:35:19.918Z","parentId":"32d950fa-512a-45c9-abba-70fda10fe6a1"}
